          rec: "Automated circuit breaking by service mesh with ML-enhanced anomaly detection. Envoy's outlier detection handles the common cases (consecutive 5xx, latency outliers), but at this scale you also need: (1) Adaptive thresholds — a static '50% failure rate' threshold doesn't work when some services have 0.001% baseline error rate and others have 2%. ML models learn each dependency's normal behavior and detect anomalies relative to its baseline. (2) Automatic fallback routing — when a breaker opens, traffic is automatically routed to a healthy replica in another cell/region rather than returning a degraded response. The user never sees degradation. (3) Predictive circuit breaking — if a dependency's latency is trending upward (e.g., p99 went from 50ms → 100ms → 200ms over the last 5 minutes), open the breaker proactively BEFORE it causes failures, and route traffic to a healthy replica. This prevents the degradation from ever being user-visible. (4) Breaker telemetry pipeline — all breaker state changes (trip, close, half-open) are emitted as events to a central analytics system, enabling fleet-wide reliability dashboards and trend analysis.",
